<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,386,1455]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,458,483]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Belongs to the 
<taxonomicName box="[509,632,458,483]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schoorli">
<emphasis box="[509,632,458,483]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">S. schoorli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. The combination of a brown scaling of forewing’s base, very short lateral lobes of vinculum, and two almost equally large horn-like cornuti (rate: 1:1.2; the longer cornutus twice exceeds the width of phallus) distinguishes 
<taxonomicName box="[710,845,531,555]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epicosma">
<emphasis box="[710,845,531,555]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">S. epicosma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the most resembling members of the group (
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alticosma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">S. alticosma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[326,485,567,590]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paracosma" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[326,485,567,590]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">S. paracosma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[498,593,566,591]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[498,593,566,591]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
). From similar 
<taxonomicName box="[787,913,566,591]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schoorli">
<emphasis box="[787,913,566,591]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">S. schoorli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[979,1097,566,591]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hamata">
<emphasis box="[979,1097,566,591]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">S. hamata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1117,1257,567,590]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epicosma">
<emphasis box="[1117,1257,567,590]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">S. epicosma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be easily distinguished by the the shiny median fascia of forewing and rounded inner lobe of valva.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,386,1455]" box="[199,1173,638,663]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,638,663]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[275,358,638,663]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1943,1965]" captionTargetBox="[159,1431,207,1912]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,193,1922]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 33. Adults of the central Andean Nepticulidae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556881/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
). Described in 
<bibRefCitation author="Puplesis" box="[527,831,638,663]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Puplesis, R. &amp; Robinson, G. S. (2000) A review of the Central and South American Nepticulidae (Lepidoptera) with special reference to Belize. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum, London (Entomology), 69 (1), 1 - 114." type="journal article" year="2000">Puplesis &amp; Robinson 2000</bibRefCitation>
: 28. Wingspan: about 
<quantity box="[1080,1169,639,663]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="4.1">4.1 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,386,1455]" box="[199,586,674,699]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,286,674,699]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Female</emphasis>
. Unknown (see Remarks).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,386,1455]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,376,710,735]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Male genitalia</emphasis>
. Illustrated in 
<bibRefCitation author="Puplesis" box="[562,888,710,735]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Puplesis, R. &amp; Robinson, G. S. (2000) A review of the Central and South American Nepticulidae (Lepidoptera) with special reference to Belize. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum, London (Entomology), 69 (1), 1 - 114." type="journal article" year="2000">Puplesis &amp; Robinson 2000</bibRefCitation>
: figs 99–101 (figs 102, 103 were incorrectly identified and assigned to 
<taxonomicName box="[445,579,747,771]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epicosma">
<emphasis box="[445,579,747,771]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">S. epicosma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; they belong to 
<taxonomicName authority="Remeikis &amp; Stonis" authorityName="Remeikis &amp; Stonis" box="[760,1133,746,771]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paracosma" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[760,913,747,771]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">S. paracosma</emphasis>
Remeikis &amp; Stonis
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1145,1232,746,771]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1145,1227,746,771]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">sp. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,386,1455]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,782,807]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Bionomics</emphasis>
. The species was reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Vargas" box="[662,818,783,807]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Vargas, H. A. (2011) Stigmella epicosma (Meyrick) (Lepidoptera: Nepticulidae): first distribution records from Chile and first host plant record. Neotropical Entomology, 4 (1), 152 - 153." type="journal article" year="2011">Vargas (2011)</bibRefCitation>
on native shrubs of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Kunth) D. Don" authorityName="(Kunth) D. Don" box="[1045,1432,782,807]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Trixis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cacalioides">
<emphasis box="[1045,1244,782,807]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Trixis cacalioides</emphasis>
(Kunth) D. Don
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[151,277,819,843]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
, growing in the coastal valleys of northern Chile and Peru. Larvae mine in August and December. Cocoon cream white (
<bibRefCitation author="Vargas" box="[397,541,855,879]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Vargas, H. A. (2011) Stigmella epicosma (Meyrick) (Lepidoptera: Nepticulidae): first distribution records from Chile and first host plant record. Neotropical Entomology, 4 (1), 152 - 153." type="journal article" year="2011">Vargas 2011</bibRefCitation>
). Adults fly in August and December.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,386,1455]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,890,915]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Distribution</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[360,427,890,915]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 11" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1932,1955]" captionTargetBox="[172,1411,209,1896]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[153,1433,193,1911]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 11. Distribution of the central Andean Nepticulidae. 9, species recorded at altitudes below 3700 m; 10, 11, some collecting areas in Peru. * — Stigmella epicosma Meyrick is also known from Arica Province, northern Chile (Vargas 2011); ** – S. inca sp. nov. is also discovered in southern Ecuador." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556876/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) This species occurs in 
<collectingCountry box="[693,744,891,914]" name="Peru" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[759,821,890,915]" country="Peru" name="Lima" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Lima</collectingRegion>
) at altitudes about 
<quantity box="[1033,1106,890,915]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="m" value="150.0">150 m</quantity>
; recently it was also recorded from two coastal valleys in the desert of northern 
<collectingCountry box="[708,772,926,951]" name="Chile" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Chile</collectingCountry>
, Arica Province (
